<div id="review_3406934689" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3406934689" />
    <a title="CTEP" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/116812917-ctep"><img alt="CTEP" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3406934689?book_show_action=true">Jun 23, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="CTEP" class="user" itemprop="url" name="CTEP" href="/user/show/116812917-ctep">CTEP</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/116812917-ctep?shelf=2011-12">2011-12</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3406934689" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15607315230570969552">During the month of February I read the compilation of Dr. King speeches named &quot;A Call to Conscience&quot;. I greatly enjoyed this work and highly recommend it for anyone who is looking to study more about civil rights movements, racial segregation of the early 50&apos;s and 60&apos;s, black history, or in general Dr. King Jr. himself. Each speech is brought into perspective by an introduction of the time, the place, and the man by one of Dr. King Jr.&apos;s acquaintances. Respected names like Rosa Parks, the (four</span>
  <span id="freeText15607315230570969552" style="display:none">During the month of February I read the compilation of Dr. King speeches named "A Call to Conscience". I greatly enjoyed this work and highly recommend it for anyone who is looking to study more about civil rights movements, racial segregation of the early 50's and 60's, black history, or in general Dr. King Jr. himself. Each speech is brought into perspective by an introduction of the time, the place, and the man by one of Dr. King Jr.'s acquaintances. Respected names like Rosa Parks, the (fourteenth) Dalai Lama, and Aretha Franklin give light to the context and circumstance of the day the speech was given, and their personal views of Martin Luther King Jr. as a civil rights leader. <br /><br />I liked how the book arranges the speeches in chronological order. In this way it acts as a biography as the reader can see the progress of Dr. King’s leadership through his speeches. I also greatly enjoyed the fact that the speeches are written from a live audio recording and they include the audience’s responses and reactions throughout the speech. Because of this, I found myself reading each speech very slowly with the sound of Dr. King’s voice ringing through my head and the crowd’s reactions echoing in the background.<br /><br />Reading this book gave me a deep respect for Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. I was familiar with his most famous speeches before this book, but there are several (Birth of a New Nation, Acceptance of the Nobel Peace Prize) that I had never heard and greatly enjoyed. Dr. King’s persistence for a nonviolent movement is most respectful. He statement that freedom is not won, it is earned, alone explains the profound intelligence of this man. <br /><br />Although racial equality has improved from the 1950’s/1960’s, this book has also made me realize that the situation of the African American has not changed that much in perspective. Many black Americans still reside in low-income neighborhoods with high rates of violence, unemployment and kids dropping out of school. In addition to that, the majority of upper class American citizens are still Caucasian. In response to this, next month I will be reading “The Myth of Black Progress” to further investigate my observation. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15607315230570969552" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


